---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Navigation from "../../components/Navigation.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";
---

<Layout title="HisabProx Case Study">
  <Navigation />

  <main id="main-content" class="flex-1 max-w-[68ch] mx-auto px-6 py-16 sm:py-24 flex flex-col gap-12 font-sans">
    
    <!-- Top Bar Navigation -->
    <div class="text-xs text-[#71717A] font-mono border-b border-[rgba(255,255,255,0.06)] pb-4">
      <a href="/work" class="hover:text-[#FAFAFA] transition-colors">← Back to Work</a>
    </div>

    <!-- Header -->
    <header class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <div class="flex gap-2 text-xs text-[#71717A] font-mono uppercase tracking-wider">
        <span>Archive</span>
        <span>·</span>
        <span>2024</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-display font-medium text-[#FAFAFA] tracking-tight leading-tight">
        HisabProx: Invoice Compiler
      </h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-[#A1A1AA] italic">
        "A local invoice generation tool built to let developers compile PDF invoices completely offline."
      </p>
    </header>

    <!-- Project Snapshot -->
    <section class="border-y border-[rgba(255,255,255,0.06)] py-6 text-xs font-mono text-[#A1A1AA] flex flex-col gap-2">
      <div>Role: <span class="text-white">Founder</span></div>
      <div>Duration: <span class="text-white">2024</span></div>
      <div>Status: <span class="text-white">● Archived</span></div>
      <div>Team: <span class="text-white">1 Engineer</span></div>
      <div>Stack: <span class="text-white">TypeScript · React · Local Storage · PDFKit</span></div>
      <div>Repository: <span class="text-white">Open Source</span></div>
    </section>

    <!-- Case Study Content -->
    <div class="flex flex-col gap-12 text-[#FAFAFA] text-base leading-[1.7] tracking-tight font-normal">
      
      <!-- Context -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Context</h2>
        <p>
          HisabProx is an offline invoice generation tool built for developers, designers, and freelancers.
          Rather than route business financial operations, client details, and rate metrics through remote cloud hosting environments,
          HisabProx keeps all records contained inside the user's browser runtime.
          The project provides a private, zero-setup option for invoicing.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Constraints -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Constraints</h2>
        <p>
          The application must operate offline and require no backend server database dependencies.
          This constraint eliminates server maintenance costs and guarantees data privacy.
          However, compiling invoice templates into PDF binaries must be handled entirely in client-side browser threads
          without causing interface lag.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Alternatives Considered -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Alternatives Considered</h2>
        <p>
          We originally considered generating PDF documents by using standard CSS print layouts inside the browser print dialog.
          While simple, browser print engines render fonts, margins, and page breaks inconsistently across devices.
          We also evaluated sending JSON data to an external API endpoint that compiles documents on a remote server.
          We rejected this pattern to prevent sensitive client data from leaving the local host.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Trade-offs -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Trade-offs</h2>
        <p>
          We traded multi-device cloud synchronization for zero hosting costs and total data privacy.
          If a user clears their browser local storage or switches to a new machine, their history is not synced.
          To mitigate this limitation without compromising privacy,
          we created a system for manual JSON export and import backups.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Failures -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Failures</h2>
        <p>
          Our first iteration included an automated synchronization feature using a third-party cloud database.
          Managing user authentication flows and endpoint security keys added maintenance overhead.
          This compromised the data privacy promise.
          We removed the cloud sync layer entirely to keep the tool offline-only.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Monitoring -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Monitoring</h2>
        <p>
          Because there is no remote server, traditional backend monitoring is impossible.
          Instead, we set up local console auditing inside development builds to monitor local storage quota limits.
          Since browser storage is restricted to 5MB, we alert developers if data utilization exceeds 80%.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Scaling Considerations -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Scaling Considerations</h2>
        <p>
          If a user logs thousands of invoice records, local storage capacity constraints can trigger write failures.
          To handle larger datasets, we designed an migration path to the IndexedDB API.
          IndexedDB provides higher storage limits and handles complex records query indexing.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- If I Rebuilt It Today -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">If I Rebuilt It Today</h2>
        <p>
          If I started over, I would use IndexedDB from the beginning rather than standard local storage.
          IndexedDB provides asynchronous transaction handling and eliminates the risk of blocking the main thread.
          I would also choose a lighter PDF compiler library than PDFKit to reduce client bundle weight.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Source Code -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3 border-t border-[rgba(255,255,255,0.06)] pt-6">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Source Code</h2>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-4 text-xs font-mono">
          <a href="https://github.com/programmer-nick234/hisabprox" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-[#2563EB] hover:underline">
            GitHub Repository
          </a>
        </div>
      </section>

    </div>

    <!-- Tech Stack footer -->
    <footer class="flex flex-col gap-6 border-t border-[rgba(255,255,255,0.08)] pt-8 mt-4 text-xs font-mono text-[#71717A]">
      <span>Technologies: TypeScript · React · Local Storage · PDFKit · Tailwind CSS</span>
    </footer>

  </main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
